            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Preyer refers to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5712.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">W. Müller 1871</ref>; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7721.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from William Preyer, 27 April 1871</ref> and n. 5. The enclosed note from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3076.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Wilhelm Müller</ref> has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7721.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from William Preyer, 27 April 1871</ref> and n. 7, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7729.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to William Preyer, 30 April 1871</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Carl Gegenbaur.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">CD cited <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5976.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Josef Hyrtl</ref> on human ears in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 1: 20 n. 23, on <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_815.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Giovanni Canestrini’s</ref> authority.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">CD had asked whether hedgehog ears were shaped like human ears. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7729.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to William Preyer, 30 April 1871</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7">See the enclosed drawing.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f8">The reference is to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4116.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Peter Paul Rubens’s</ref> painting, <hi rend="italic">The drunken Hercules</hi>, in the Gemäldegallerie, Dresden.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f9"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2814.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edwin Ray Lankester</ref> was studying under <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2048.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ernst Haeckel</ref> at Jena; he also visited Leipzig and Vienna (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5933.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi></ref>). Botocudos was the name given by Europeans to a native people in eastern Brazil. The name is from the Portuguese word (botoque) for ‘plug’, and refers to the ornaments that were worn in the ears and lower lip (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2248.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">EB</hi></ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f10">The diagram is reproduced at 66 per cent of its original size.</note>
        </div>        
            
